   Date: 11 Apr 86 11:18:39 EST (Fri)
   From: "Paul M. Albitz" &lt;albitz@Purdue.EDU&gt;

   I am in the cs subdomain at host w.  To access host x, I can use the names
   x.cs.purdue.edu or x (for which the resolver tacks on cs.purdue.edu since
   it is my default domain.)

   To access host y, I must use the name y.ecn.purdue.edu.

   What I would like to do is access host y using the name y.ecn execpt that
   since it has a '.' in the name, it is assumed to be a fully specified domain
   name.

One easy-to-implement compromise would be for you to specify
y.ecn.purdue, leaving off the .edu.  Your mailer would recognize the purdue
in its own hostname, and therefore try to complete y.ecn.purdue by tacking
on a .edu.  In other words, instead of the address containing up to the
first common subdomain, it should contain up to AND INCLUDING the first
common subdomain.
